A financial services company is migrating their legacy application to \textbf{Amazon EC2} instances running on \textbf{AWS}. The application requires read and write access to sensitive data stored in \textbf{Amazon S3} and must retrieve database credentials from \textbf{AWS Secrets Manager}. The company has strict security policies:

\begin{itemize}
\item Credentials must never be stored on EC2 instances
\item Access permissions must follow the \textit{principle of least privilege}
\item A developer who previously left the company retained an \textbf{IAM User} access key; the security team needs to guarantee this key can no longer be used
\item The solution must support temporary credentials with automatic rotation
\end{itemize}

Which combination of approaches \textbf{BEST} meets all these requirements?

explanation:
\textbf{B is correct:}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{IAM Roles} attached to \textbf{EC2 instances} provide temporary security credentials via the instance metadata service — credentials are never stored on the instance and are automatically rotated by \textbf{AWS}
\item Managed policies enable modular, version-controlled permission management aligned with \textit{least privilege}; custom managed policies can be refined with conditions to grant only the minimum required permissions
\item Deactivating the legacy \textbf{IAM User} access key immediately revokes that user's ability to authenticate — the security requirement is met
\item This approach uses temporary credentials (via \textbf{AWS STS}) rather than long-lived keys
\end{itemize}

\textbf{A is incorrect:} Attaching an \textbf{IAM User} to an \textbf{EC2 instance} is not valid; \textbf{Users} are for people and applications with long-lived credentials, not for compute resources. Inline policies reduce auditability and reusability compared to managed policies.

\textbf{C is incorrect:} While deleting the user is a valid approach, \textbf{IMDSv2} is a metadata service security enhancement — it does not grant permissions itself. Resource-based policies are not attached to \textbf{IAM Roles}; they are attached to resources like \textbf{S3 buckets} or \textbf{SQS queues}.

\textbf{D is incorrect:} Storing credentials in \textbf{EC2 user data} directly violates the stated requirement that credentials must never be stored on instances. Additionally, a \textbf{Deny Policy} on the \textbf{IAM User} does not remove or revoke existing access keys — the legacy key could still be used for other authenticated actions unless explicitly deactivated or deleted.
